## Agent Workstreams
- Agent 01: source registry and schema persistence.
- Agent 02: frontier scoring and crawl scheduler.
- Agent 03: RSS/static web adapters.
- Agent 04: Telegram public channel adapter and compliance notes.
- Agent 05: Tor/I2P/Freenet metadata adapter design and safe fetch interfaces.
- Agent 06: raw evidence store and deduplication.
- Agent 07: text extraction, IOC/entity extraction, and confidence scoring.
- Agent 08: ATT&CK/STIX/TAXII mapping and export contracts.
- Agent 09: API endpoints, operational health, and metrics.
- Agent 10: deployment, observability, resource controls, and Inspur runbook.
  - 2026-05-24: restoring missing `src/frontier/frontier.ts` and adding ops-owned runtime config, resource budgets, structured logs, metrics, worker supervision, and runbook/capacity docs. Shared API health responses may include runtime, resource, and metrics snapshots.

## Integration Contract
- Adapters return `AdapterRunResult`.
- New source types must be added to `SourceType`.
- Sources now use an expanded lifecycle in `SourceStatus`: `candidate`, `needs_review`, `approved`, `active`, `probation`, `degraded`, `quarantined`, `paused`, `disabled`, `retired`, and `rejected`.
- Medium, high, and restricted sources require explicit governance approval fields before they can become `active`; darknet metadata sources must also stay `metadataOnly`.
- Source records may include `health`, `scoring`, `governance`, `crawlState`, and `tags` sections. Consumers should treat missing sections as unset defaults, not as approval.
- Agent 01 owns `SourceReviewDecision` for source approve/reject/expire/quarantine/restore governance actions. Agent 09 source-admin APIs should accept this shape when adding review endpoints.
- Agent 01 seed bundles live under `seeds/` as versioned JSON fixtures for safe public CTI sources only. Importers validate and report duplicates by tenant/type/canonical URL; they must not trigger live crawling.
- Agent 01 source catalog metadata now describes publisher identity, source tier, approval scope, topic/actor/industry/region coverage, SLA/freshness targets, retention class, rollback state, adapter compatibility, and activation status. Agent 09 `/v1/sources` and future `/v1/intel/search` responses should preserve these fields for source coverage explanations.
- Source activation reporting classifies sources as `active`, `approved_idle`, `candidate_only`, `blocked_by_policy`, `missing_legal_notes`, `stale`, `duplicate`, or `adapter_incompatible` for a query. Agent 02 skipped-source reasons should reuse these categories where possible.
- Agent 01 Task I source activation API contracts expose `/v1/intel/search`-ready active coverage, approved-idle coverage, candidate gaps, legal/policy/stale/duplicate/adapter gaps, deterministic underserved reasons, and dry-run-only safe public source-pack install plans. Agent 09 can surface these contracts without triggering crawling.
- Agent 01 Task J registry reconciliation uses stable drift reason codes for missing approved sources, approved-not-scheduled sources, unhealthy active sources, active sources without recent captures, policy-disabled sources, expired approvals, stale legal notes, duplicates, and adapter capability mismatches. Agent 02 skipped-source reasons should reuse or map to these codes when scheduler state is the cause.
- Agent 01 Task K source cutover rehearsals produce API-ready source readiness artifacts combining activation coverage, reconciliation drift, dry-run source-pack install plans, source-health summaries, governance evidence, blockers, rollback/quarantine state, and promotion-gate fields for Agent 10 deployment drift checks.
- Agent 01 Task L source apply-plan boundary converts cutover/reconciliation recommendations into dry-run-only registry mutation plans with prerequisites, expected diffs, rollback state, policy/collection impact, and automation safety classification. `/v1/sources` may expose these plans, but no production mutation is performed by plan generation.
- Agent 01 Task M freezes `/v1/sources/apply-plan` API DTOs around source apply plans: compact request/response shapes, selected actions, approval counts, dry-run execution preview, schema-ready examples, and promotion-packet link fields. DTOs must never imply mutation, crawling, or restricted-source auto-activation.
- Agent 01 Task N provides mountable `/v1/sources/apply-plan` route-handler helpers and JSON-schema-like contracts for Agent 09. Handlers validate selected actions and dry-run semantics, return safe error bodies, and never mutate registry state or start crawling.
- Agent 01 Task O proves the mounted `/v1/sources/apply-plan` route through the Bun API server and `bun run check:source-apply-plan`. The proof covers happy path, blocked restricted source, and invalid action responses, and asserts source/frontier snapshots stay unchanged with no crawling or registry mutation fields.
- Agent 01 Task P provides production source onboarding coverage contracts for `/v1/sources/coverage-plan` and `/v1/intel/search` source coverage. DTOs summarize active coverage, approved-idle sources, missing verticals, stale/policy/adapter gaps, safe source-pack recommendations, forbidden source classes, and dry-run install semantics without crawling or registry mutation.
- Agent 01 Task Q promotes source coverage into runtime actor-query planning. `/v1/intel/search` and `/v1/sources/coverage-plan` coverage DTOs now distinguish eligible, selected, idle, stale, blocked, and missing approved public sources, include governance drift findings, and expose dry-run remediation plans for activation, quarantine, cadence/legal review, adapter reassignment, and duplicate retirement.
- Agent 01 Task R adds enforcement-grade source coverage SLO contracts. `/v1/intel/search` source coverage and `/v1/sources/coverage-plan` query rows expose `slo` and `drift` fields for minimum safe-public active source count, source-family diversity, freshness, geographic/sector coverage, and legal/robots completeness; coverage state may be `needs_review` when safe discovery can continue but SLOs fail. Enforcement plans remain dry-run-only and never let restricted, private, credentialed, leaked-file, chat, auth, or CAPTCHA-gated sources satisfy public-source SLOs.
- Agent 01 Task S adds source portfolio operations contracts. `/v1/sources/portfolio` and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage.portfolio` expose dry-run source family, actor, region, sector, language, legal/robots review age, reliability, and extraction-yield groupings plus source-pack onboarding plans, SLO burn-down actions, scheduler-cost estimates, parser compatibility, rollback/quarantine state, and promotion-safety fields. Portfolio recommendations remain non-crawling and cannot count restricted, leaked, private, auth, CAPTCHA, or public-chat sources as safe-public SLO coverage.
- Agent 01 Task T adds source activation batch contracts for runtime collection readiness. `/v1/sources/activation-batches` and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage.activationBatch` expose dry-run operator decision packets that combine portfolio/SLO burn-down, legal and robots review state, scheduler queue/cadence impact, parser compatibility, rollback/quarantine state, retention, max bytes, adapter ownership, and safe-public rationale. Activation batches never mutate, crawl, or admit restricted, private, leaked, auth, CAPTCHA, or public-chat sources into safe-public activation.
- Agent 01 Task U adds source runtime SLA contracts. `/v1/sources/runtime-sla`, `/v1/sources/activation-batches`, and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage.runtimeSla` expose dry-run freshness, capture success ratio, parser compatibility, legal/robots review age, scheduler cost, evidence yield, claim yield, rollback, and quarantine state plus breach remediation for source activation, noisy-source pause, quarantine, legal/robots review, cadence change, duplicate retirement, and Agent 03 parser-support requests. Runtime SLA planning never mutates registry/frontier state or starts crawling.
- Agent 01 Task V adds source SLA enforcement and promotion-gate contracts. `/v1/sources/runtime-sla`, `/v1/sources/activation-batches`, and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage` expose compact promotion holds, warnings, dry-run repair packets, source-family coverage gates by query class, Agent 02 scheduler-cost holds, Agent 03 parser-gap holds, Agent 06 evidence-yield holds, and Agent 10 release-decision fields. Enforcement gates are planning-only and never mutate sources, leases, queues, or crawl state.
- Agent 01 Task W adds source coverage closeout and safe activation-wave contracts. `/v1/sources/coverage-closeout`, `/v1/sources/activation-batches`, and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage.coverageCloseout` expose query-family readiness for actor, ransomware/victim, CVE, malware/tool, country, sector, campaign, and infrastructure searches plus dry-run activation waves for at least 50 safe public CTI sources across vendor blogs, advisories, RSS, GitHub/security advisories, public research feeds, and government CERT sources. Closeout waves include approval scope, legal/robots freshness, parser compatibility, scheduler budget, expected evidence yield, rollback/quarantine plan, and Agent 07/09/10 promotion impact; unsafe source classes remain excluded from safe-public coverage.
- Agent 01 Task X adds source activation execution-readiness contracts. `/v1/sources/coverage-closeout`, `/v1/sources/activation-batches`, `/v1/contracts`, and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage` expose dry-run first-10 canary packets, 50-source public rollout packets, excluded unsafe/parser-gap/duplicate source proofs, legal/robots proof ages, parser ownership, Agent 02 queue budget impact, rollback/quarantine triggers, post-activation drift checks, source retirement and duplicate-suppression plans, Agent 03 parser-gap handoff, and Agent 10 release-packet fields. Execution readiness is non-mutating, non-crawling, and keeps restricted, private, leaked, auth, CAPTCHA, invite, and public-chat sources out of safe-public rollout coverage.
- Agent 01 Task Z adds source rollout promotion packet and post-canary monitoring contracts. `/v1/sources/coverage-closeout`, `/v1/sources/activation-batches`, `/v1/contracts`, and `/v1/intel/search.sourceCoverage` expose dry-run canary-to-expanded rollout promotion DTOs for actor, ransomware/victim, CVE, malware/tool, country, sector, campaign, and infrastructure coverage. Promotion packets include public `/ti` answer effects, Agent 02 scheduler telemetry, Agent 06 evidence certification, Agent 07 polling states, Agent 09 contract-index fields, Agent 10 canary/release decisions, evidence-yield thresholds, rollback criteria, cost controls, source retirement, duplicate suppression, parser-gap handoff, and post-activation drift monitoring. Promotion packets remain safe-public-only, non-mutating, and non-crawling.
- `/ti` application responses should expose analyst-loop state directly: `queued`, `metadata_review`, `blocked_unsafe_target`, `needs_source_activation`, and `ready`. Metadata-review surfaces may include victim/company, affected accounts, dataset size, actor statement, claimed date, provenance/hash, allowed analyst actions, and redacted victim-notification packets. They must also state what was not accessed: raw leaked files, credentials, private communities, CAPTCHA/auth bypass, and threat-actor interaction.
- Agent 03 crawl-state and health signals should map into `SourceHealth`, `SourceCrawlState`, and score history without changing adapter collection semantics.
- Frontier workers consume `FrontierCandidate` and enqueue `CollectionTask`; Agent 02 owns optional scheduling metadata on those contracts for leases, acknowledgements, per-source limits, retry/backoff, crawl cadence, deadlines, byte/task budgets, and fair queue selection.
- Pipeline accepts `CollectedItem` and returns `PipelineResult`.
- Storage implementations should satisfy `ScraperStore`.
- CTI applications should call the scraper through typed intelligence requests. A request like `APT29` becomes a `CollectionPlan` with clear-web tasks, API/RSS tasks, public-chat tasks, and approved metadata-only darknet tasks.
- Agent 09 owns the `/v1` enterprise API surface: typed envelopes, request planning, idempotent run creation, run status/results, source admin, captures, incidents, metrics, and API tests. API routes should stay compact and versioned under `/v1`; legacy unversioned aliases are compatibility-only.
- Agent 02 live-search planner DTOs expose deterministic `reuseKey` values plus `backpressureState`/reason/retry fields so Agent 09 can surface public `/ti` attachment, deferral, policy block, and source-activation states without creating duplicate runs.
- Agent 02 frontier scheduling treats planner budget classes as fairness inputs; interactive public live search must not starve analyst deep dives, source-health probes, retention/replay-style work, or long-running background sweeps.
- Agent 02 scheduler production diagnostics are available from `/v1/frontier.scheduler`: backend cutover design, load-model fixtures, starvation signals, active-run GC decisions, work class, reuse key, pressure state, queue age, fairness group, duplicate count, and next actionable time.
- Agent 02 scheduler runtime repository contract now covers enqueue, lease, acknowledge, retry/backoff, run reuse, active-run GC, pressure DTOs, and cursor-visible deltas; the in-memory implementation is the test double for future Postgres-backed leasing.
- Agent 02 scheduler reconciliation emits stable reason codes for source/run/task drift, queued/leased/backoff/dead-letter state, active-run reuse, abandoned/stale runs, queue pressure, and low-priority deferral, plus repair actions for Agent 09/10 operator surfaces.
- Agent 02 scheduler cutover rehearsal reports combine reconciliation, pressure DTOs, fairness simulation, active-run reuse, deterministic dry-run repair plans, and Agent 10 promotion-gate fields: p95 queue age, abandoned runs, duplicate reuse rate, retry debt, dead-letter rate, low-priority deferral, and emergency brake state.
- Agent 02 scheduler apply plans are dry-run-only and include preconditions, expected queue/run deltas, rollback notes, risk class, operator approval state, Agent 09 API warning codes, noisy-source pause actions, and emergency-brake semantics that protect API/frontend/DB headroom while preserving cursor and replay state.
- Agent 02 freezes `/v1/frontier/apply-plan` as the scheduler repair API contract: compact request/response DTOs, schema-ready examples for every action, execution previews that prove no mutation/leasing/acknowledgement/run change, and promotion-packet links for Agent 10.
- Agent 02 exposes `/v1/frontier/apply-plan` through a mountable route helper with dry-run enforcement, selected-action validation, safe error bodies, non-mutating frontier snapshots, cursor/replay preservation, and contract tests for every scheduler repair action.
- Agent 02 mounted endpoint proof is `bun run check:frontier-apply-plan`; it starts the Bun API server, posts normal/degraded/emergency/invalid-action requests to `/v1/frontier/apply-plan`, and expects `ok: true` with unchanged queue, lease, and run snapshots.
- Agent 02 continuous actor-query scheduling now enqueues run-scoped tasks from `/v1/intel/runs`, reuses active duplicate actor/CVE runs, exposes scheduler summaries on `/v1/intel/search`, `/v1/intel/runs/{id}`, and `/v1/frontier/status`, and preserves dry-run-only apply-plan semantics.
- Agent 02 scheduler runtime contracts now include worker heartbeat/checkpoint deltas, cancellation, retry/backoff, stale active-run and duplicate-query handling, 24h soak fixtures, and polling summary fields: `nextPollAt`, `cursorContinuity`, `latestCursor`, `promotedEvidenceCount`, `newEvidenceDeltaCount`, and `partialReasons`.
- Agent 02 scheduler execution simulation now emits deterministic 24h SLO/backpressure packets for actor traffic, sweeps, public-channel windows, restricted approvals, evidence replay, graph export, and retention jobs, with Agent 09 compatibility fields and Agent 10 soak packet decisions.
- Agent 02 scheduler worker-loop economics now define production contracts for leasing, heartbeat, checkpoint, cancellation, retry/backoff, stale-lease recovery, duplicate run reuse, abandoned-client cleanup, and cursor continuity; `/v1/intel/search.scheduler`, `/v1/frontier/status`, and Agent 10 soak packets expose queue economics plus dry-run capacity-shift plans across interactive, public-channel, restricted metadata, replay, graph export, retention, and sweep work.
- Agent 02 runtime scheduler execution bridge now exposes route-visible execution state for queued, leased, checkpointed, retried, acknowledged, cancelled, dead-lettered, and stale-recovered tasks by run, source, and work class; scheduler summaries include cursor-safe runtime deltas, activation budget guards, and dry-run controls for noisy sources, background deferral, public-channel reduction, restricted metadata holds, and source activation batch holds.
- Agent 02 scheduler runtime SLA now exposes lease latency, checkpoint freshness, retry debt, dead-letter growth, abandoned-client cleanup, run reuse, fairness, source SLA pressure, and cursor continuity with public/API impact, dry-run worker safety plans, stale-lease recovery safeguards, and Agent 10 release-packet decisions.
- Agent 02 scheduler SLA enforcement now emits compact release-gate holds/warnings for queue age, lease age, checkpoint gaps, retry debt, dead letters, abandoned clients, duplicate run reuse, fairness drift, source SLA pressure, and cursor discontinuity, plus dry-run live-run drain plans for overloaded live search, public-channel backlogs, restricted metadata holds, graph export backlog, evidence replay load, source activation waves, stale leases, and cursor replay.
- Agent 02 production worker queue cutover now exposes a Bun worker runtime contract with partitions for interactive actor search, scheduled sweeps, public-channel windows, restricted metadata approvals, evidence replay, graph export, retention, and health probes; route summaries include lease/checkpoint/ack/retry/dead-letter semantics, 96 GB/160 GB capacity envelopes, and dry-run Postgres/Redis/NATS backend cutover packets.
- Agent 02 runtime worker soak and backend migration planning now exposes 24h per-partition SLOs, p95/p99 queue age, checkpoint cadence, retry debt/dead-letter budgets, memory pressure, run reuse, duplicate public polling, safe drain controls, embedded-to-Postgres/Redis/NATS migration packets, Agent 09 warning codes, route contract fields, and Agent 10 release-train proof commands.
- Agent 02 scheduler productionization adapter telemetry now defines a stable adapter interface for embedded memory plus Postgres/Redis/NATS candidates, route-visible lease throughput, ack latency, retry debt, dead-letter causes, p95/p99 queue age, cursor/replay preservation, run reuse, duplicate public polling, stale clients, heartbeats, cancellation, drain progress, 24h canary soak fixtures, Agent 09 warnings, and Agent 10 RC gate proof commands.
- The scraper must remain modular: source discovery, collection, extraction, storage, and API can be replaced independently.

## Start-Up Check Cadence
- First day: check each agent after first file read and after first patch.
- First week: twice daily coordination updates.
- Later: daily status plus blocking-change alerts.

